<section class="page-margin contained">
    <span class="small-text-14 mono eyebrow">Challenge</span>
    <h2>How might we help directional drillers get back on plan when they accidentally veer off course?</h2>
    <p>Horizontal directional drilling (HDD) or directional boring is something you may have  seen but never paid much attention to. It’s a method of installng underground utilities without needing to dig a trench or pathway to place the cables or pipe.</p>
    <p>In it’s simplest form, there are as few as  two crew members – one on the drill rig forcing large rods into the Earth to create a hole, and one out in front with something that looks like a metal detector, which is able to tell where the drill head is underground. This last person is called a locator, and they relay the information about the drill head to the drill operator in order to steer and create the hole.</p>
    <p>A global industrial equipment manufacturer wanted to update it’s propriatary on-rig directional drilling software and include a new a feature that alerts and assists operators when the intended trajectory of their drill has changed while it’s moving underground.</p>
</section>

