<section class="page-margin contained">
    <span class="small-text-14 mono eyebrow">Research</span>
    <h2>Unpacking the problem</h2>
    <p>We were first given a wish list of sorts that contained a mix of existing and new software features, including an auto-correct feature aimed at helping drillers get back on their planned path.</p>
    <p>In order to learn more about the problem domain, and, more importantly, understand the perceived user value behind these features, we spent the first 2 weeks conducting remote stakeholder interviews. Specifically, we spoke with people on the company's commercialization team who had frequent first-hand experience with customers and an understanding of the software.</p>
    <p>Through these conversations we were able to prioritize the features with our client product owner in order to form a high-level backlog for our development team. We also received a demo of the existing software to understand what would be essential to maintain market parity. This kicked off our crash course in directional drilling.</p>
</section>

<section class="page-margin contained">
    <h2>Ideation</h2>
    <p>While familiarizing ourselves with the industry and the needs of a drilling crew out in the field, I started sketching out ideas for the new interface. Without much knoweldge to that point of how a bore plan is created and executed, I began by brainstorming how we could let a drill operator know something significant happened and how they might be able to act on that information.</p>
    <p>The existing software allows drill operators to see their plan on a screen mounted on the rig, and a third-party tool helps drillers see where the drill head is at in real time. This got us thinking of how we might merge this information to create an experience similar to turn-by-turn directions in something like Google Maps or Waze.</p>
</section>

