<section class="page-margin contained">
    <h2 id="interaction-design">The FAB wheel</h2>
    <p>As the interface design matured, my research colleague and I thought about how we could make the main view of the plan cross section more actionable. Using what we learned, we talked through the actions a user may want to take when looking at the plan. We further explored how the touch screen could operate as a means of progressive disclosure, and that led us to the FAB (floating action button) wheel.</p>
    <p>Depending on the screen or object selected, different actions would be shown to the user. During my time on the project there was only a need for a 2-button and 4-button option. However, l also modeled out how other wheels would look to help my team and other designers who come on to support the project later.</p>
    <p>The ticky part came in selecting proper icons so that users were provided the correct affordance for each button. In the beginning, we were nearly spot on, but I made a few iterations over the course of several user testing sessions to make sure each icons was very clear.</p>
</section>

