<section class="page-margin contained">
    <h2 id="user-testing">Iterative testing with users</h2>
    <p>We were able to do in-person tests with a couple local drilling companies, as well as a handful of company employees who work on the manfucaturing and testing of drilling equipment. However, we also did remote user testing using an Adobe XD prototype over Zoom with 8 participants in the U.S. and Canada.</p>
    <p>Leading up to these remote sessions, I became the lone UX representative on the team and assumed the responsibilities of recruiting users and coordinating calendars in addition to the testing itself. I tested with each remote user at least twice – a couple 3 times – though they saw different features each time.</p>
    <p>Each feature I designed for testing was closely associated with a specific scenario, and I would provide participants with reference materials for context, such as a fake visual of an obstacle or mock up plans to edit. Sometimes a feature would still be an early idea, but I would test general usability and also ask for contextual feedback.</p>
    <p>The learnings from this were incredibly valuable, and I was able to make iterative changes on a weekly basis. This helped me understand at granular level how a drill operator or crew supervisor thinks and allowed me to closely map the interface to their mental model.</p>
    <blockquote class="callout page-margin contained">
    Thanks to my frequent interactions with users, by the end of my time with the team, our product owner’s supervisor commented that I knew more about HDD than some of their employees.
    </blockquote>
</section>

