<section class="page-margin contained">
    <h2>Additional design efforts</h2>
    <p>While revamping the embedded app started as the primary objective, our team was also tasked with leveraging the Windows ecosystem to create a branded, pseduo operating system so only the installed apps could be accessed from the machine.</p>
    <p>A persistent launch bar, fixed to the bottom of the screen, was created to provide quick access to all the apps installed on the device and offer a means to toggle between them while out in the field. This was the first deliverable our team completed so that other developers in the company's IT department could immediately adopt it and build companion apps.</p>
    <p>Our team also simultaneously worked on a native mobile app that had many of the same basic features as the embedded solution. A lot of the user feedback gathered helped influence what features would be essential for a MVP and what could be possibly offered behind a paywall. This app went live in the summer of 2019 and is called <a href="https://apps.apple.com/us/app/boreplan/id1467957378" target="_blank" title="BorePlan on the App Store">BorePlan, available in the Apple and Android app stores today</a>.</p>
</section>

<section class="page-margin contained">
    <span class="small-text-14 mono eyebrow">Outcome</span>
    <h2 id="ui-design">Going full bore</h2>
    <p>Not only is the new embedded app branded and better organized visually, it also gives users the freedom to create a bore plan directly on the drill. User can edit imported or locally-created plans if they happen to run into issues during execution, then they can be exported onto a portable USB drive and added to printed project reports or other deliverables once the work is complete.</p>
    <p>We also leverage a lot of the same information this equipment manufacturing company requests from users in the Projects web app around materials and hardware, which allows the system to make quick calculations, which were previously done manually by the driller or another crew member. Overall, the goal was to lower the barrier to entry for smaller crews who may not have access to the same resources available to larger companies.</p>
</section>

