<section class="page-margin contained">
    <span class="small-text-14 mono eyebrow">Reflections &amp; Learnings</span>
    <h2>What I liked</h2>
    <p>Emebedded apps were a new frontier for me. I’d mostly designed several web systems leading up to this project, so I enjoyed exploring a different platform and understanding what the possibilities and constraints were when crafting a new UI. Having collaborative teammates also help – especially when they ran into issues and we were able to research and talk through what would be possible to achieve the most desirable experience.</p>
    <h2>What I learned</h2>
    <p>I learned a lot about directional drilling – more than I ever thought I would or could. I think this is where my experience as a journalist benefits me as a UX designer. At the beginning it seemed like there was so much to learn in order to deliver a great product, but persistence and having a client team and users out in the field who were happy to educate me took me a long way. I will always remember what the colored utility flags mean when I see them on the side of the road.</p>
    <h2>What I lacked</h2>
    <p>For a while, our team lacked velocity from a delivery standpoint. While I was able to execute from a design perspective, it took several sprints for the development to catch up. By the end of my time with the team, I was already exploring feature ideas with users that wouldn’t be groomed and put in the backlog for many months. This made it challenging to maintain the same level of collaboration towards the end.</p>
    <h2>What I longed For</h2>
    <p>As I started to roll off the project, the team was in the home stretch of delivering the mobile app. I wished I could have stayed on a bit longer to provide QA or conduct user testing prior to the app going live in the app stores because there are some subtle UI differences I would have advocated against to maintain consistency with what was coming in the embedded app. All of my user testing was with a design prototype too, so it would have been great to test the real product with those same users.</p>
</section>